Colombia Stocks: Fabricato Rises; Isa, Nutresa, Aval Fall

-- B y   B l a k e   S c h m i d t
-- 
2011-05-03T20:28:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-03/colombia-stocks-fabricato-rises-isa-nutresa-aval-fall.html
The following companies are having
unusual price changes in Bogota trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IGBC Index fell for a second day by 1.4 percent to
14,113.62, while the Colcap Index dropped 1.2 percent to
1,671.95.  Grupo Aval Acciones y Valores (AVAL)  SA, Colombia’s
biggest financial holding company, fell for a second day,
dropping 0.4 percent to 1,340 pesos as investors awaited delayed
results of the company’s share issue, said Mauricio Restrepo Del Toro, research director at brokerage Bolsa y Renta.  Grupo Nutresa SA (NUTRESA CB), Colombia’s largest food
producer, formerly known as Grupo Nacional de Chocolates, fell
0.9 percent to 22,500 pesos. Cost of goods sold were higher-
than-expected in the first quarter and the company faces a
“challenging environment” as it plans to issue shares, said
 Andres Jimenez , head of international sales for Interbolsa SA,
in an e-mailed report today.  Interconexion Electrica SA (ISA)   declined for a second
day after  Barclays Capital  said the Colombian energy and
infrastructure firm is “fully valued.” The stock fell 1.6
percent to 12,300.  Textiles Fabricato Tejicondor SA (FABRI)  , Colombia’s
biggest textile maker, rose for a second day to the highest in
almost four years on speculation the company will benefit from a
free trade agreement with the U.S. and Venezuelan payments of
overdue debt, said Carlos Esteban Santiago, analyst at Alianza
Valores SA.  The stock gained 2.9 percent to 46.7 pesos.  Oil companies  dropped as crude oil fell to a two-week low
as the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index dropped and on projections
that a government report will show U.S. crude inventories
climbed.  Ecopetrol SA (ECOPETL)  , Colombia’s state-run  oil
company , fell 1.2 percent to 3,795 pesos.  Pacific Rubiales (PREC CB) fell 2.3 percent to 51,900
pesos.  Canacol Energy Ltd. (CNE)  , the Calgary-based oil
company that operates fields in South America, dropped 1.9
percent to 2,285 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blake Schmidt in Bogota at 
